---
description: Next.js frontend rules (web — Admin + User interface; native mobile is separate)
globs: frontend/**, src/**, app/**, components/**, pages/**, lib/**, hooks/**
---

This rule applies to the **web** frontend only. The project also has a **native mobile app** (separate codebase); see .cursor/rules/12-interfaces-admin-user-mobile.mdc.

Frontend stack:
- Next.js
- TypeScript
- Component-driven UI
- API integration with FastAPI backend (REST + WebSocket for chat and real-time)

Frontend rules:
- Prefer TypeScript for all frontend logic.
- Keep components small, reusable, and focused.
- Keep presentation separate from business/data-fetching logic.
- Use hooks, services, or server actions appropriately based on project style.
- Handle loading, error, and empty states explicitly.
- Preserve design consistency and naming consistency.
- Support real-time updates (WebSocket or SSE) for live chat, call status, and agent copilot suggestions.
- **Two UIs in one app:** **Admin** (e.g. `/admin/*`) and **User interface** (e.g. `/`, `/chat`, `/tickets`); use role-based routing and layout; shared design system and API client.

Product-area alignment (see docs/PRD.md):
- **Admin (web only):** AI model config, knowledge base management, agent management, system monitoring, API keys.
- **User interface (web):** Chat UI, agent dashboard, analytics dashboard; optional voice/video and channel switcher.
- **Native mobile app:** Separate codebase; not covered by this rule.

Preferred frontend structure:
- frontend/app/            (routes for Admin and User UI)
- frontend/app/admin/     (admin-only routes/layouts)
- frontend/components/
- frontend/features/       (chat, tickets, admin, analytics)
- frontend/hooks/
- frontend/lib/
- frontend/services/       (API client, WebSocket, auth)
- frontend/types/
- frontend/tests/

UI/UX rules:
- Use accessible markup and semantic HTML.
- Prefer reusable design system components.
- Avoid oversized page components.
- Avoid embedding complex API logic directly inside visual components unless already established by the repo.

State/data rules:
- Keep API clients centralized.
- Normalize repeated API access patterns.
- Handle auth state carefully.
- Validate critical inputs on both client and server.

Do not:
- Mix many responsibilities into one component.
- Hardcode API URLs in components.
- Duplicate UI patterns that should be shared.
- Put admin-only flows in the mobile app codebase (admin is web only).